                <head>427. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On February 21, 1968, President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName>
                    and <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Secretary General <persName
                        corresp="#p_UT1">U Thant</persName> met for a discussion of the Secretary
                    General’s most recent effort to find a solution to the Vietnam war. <persName
                        corresp="#p_UT1">U Thant</persName> reported that the North Vietnamese were
                    willing to begin talks “immediately” upon the cessation of U.S. bombing raids on
                    their territory. The Secretary General urged the President to undertake another
                    bombing pause to test the sincerity of the North Vietnamese. The President
                    expressed his doubts about North Vietnam’s objectives but encouraged <persName
                        corresp="#p_UT1">U Thant</persName>’s efforts. A tape recording of their
                    conversation is in the Johnson Library, Recordings and Transcripts of Cabinet
                    Room Meetings, Tape C002A–1D. A 3-page summary of the meeting and an unedited
                    transcript are ibid. Johnson discussed the meeting in The Vantage Point, page
                    395.</p>
            </div>
